## Severity Classification

| Severity | Criteria | Example | Input-Grounding Required |
|----------|----------|---------|--------------------------|
| critical | Blocks CER acceptance — NO clinical evidence found in CER text | CER text is empty or contains no clinical data | Must cite specific CER text evidence of absence |
| high | Significant gap — CER text has some content but lacks specific quantified data required by R2_F-002 | Benefit claims present but without quantitative results; risk assessment lacks explicit acceptability per risk | Must cite WHICH specific CER text section is missing WHICH specific data |
| medium | Notable gap — evidence is present but quality or format needs improvement | Benefits described but not tabulated; risks listed but without individual acceptability statements | Must identify WHAT is present and WHAT needs improvement |
| low | Enhancement opportunity — evidence is adequate, minor improvements possible | Source refs present but format could be more structured | Must acknowledge existing evidence quality |

**IMPORTANT**: HIGH severity MUST be justified with specific content analysis. You MUST cite:
1. WHAT the CER text contains (quote or paraphrase)
2. WHAT specific requirement from R2_F-002 is NOT met
3. WHERE in the CER text the missing information SHOULD appear
4. WHY this gap is significant enough to warrant HIGH severity

If you cannot provide ALL FOUR justifications, the severity MUST be downgraded to medium or lower.

